{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488890"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:01:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:01:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"566"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/566"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.06,0.24,0.43,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"566"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53565"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/566"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"566"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39008"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3732"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"46"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14038"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15903"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53565"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman is newly diagnosed with Diffuse Large B-cell Lymphoma, stage III. She has a history of hypertension well-managed on perindopril.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her pulse rate is 95/min and regular, blood pressure 130/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, oxygenation 92% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is cervical, axillary, and inguinal lymphadenopathy measuring 2-3 cm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter discussion in the lymphoma multidisciplinary team meeting, she is planned to commence rituximab, cyclophosphamide, doxorubicin, vincristine, and prednisone (R-CHOP), an anthracycline-containing regimen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following tests should be requested before commencing treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pulmonary function test","CT coronary angiogram","Bone mineral density scan","Transthoracic echocardiogram","HLA typing"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAnthracycline (e.g., doxorubicin, idarubicin) is a commonly used chemotherapeutic used in different malignancies, such as Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (DLBCL) and breast cancer. Their mechanism of action involves intercalation between DNA bases and the inhibition of topoisomerase II. However, there is a risk of cardiotoxicity associated with anthracycline therapy. Hence, evaluation of left ventricular ejection fraction by gated heart pool scan or \u003Cstrong\u003Etransthoracic echocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is important before commencing therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary function test\u003C/strong\u003E is not required before starting R-CHOP therapy. While pulmonary function tests are important in the context of certain chemotherapeutic agents like bleomycin, which can cause pulmonary toxicity, they are not necessary for anthracycline-based regimens. Bleomycin is used in the treatment of Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT coronary angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is not relevant to the immediate management of this patient\u2019s lymphoma and is not required before starting R-CHOP therapy. It is typically used to assess coronary artery disease, which is not the primary concern in this context.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone mineral density scan \u003C/strong\u003E(e.g., Dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry) is not relevant to the immediate management of this patient\u2019s lymphoma and is not required before starting R-CHOP therapy. It should be considered in patients who received prolonged, high-dose glucocorticoids due to the risk of osteopenia and osteoporosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHLA typing\u003C/strong\u003E is not required before starting R-CHOP therapy. HLA typing is typically performed in the context of bone marrow or stem cell transplantation to look for a compatible donor, which is not immediately relevant to the initiation of R-CHOP therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anthracycline (e.g., doxorubicin, idarubicin) is a commonly used chemotherapeutic.","The mechanism of action involves intercalation between DNA bases and the inhibition of topoisomerase II.","There is a risk of cardiotoxicity associated with anthracycline therapy."],"references":["Limat S, Daguindau E, Cahn JY, Nerich V, Brion A, Perrin S, et al. Incidence and risk-factors of CHOP/R-CHOP-related cardiotoxicity in patients with aggressive non-Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma. J Clin Pharm Ther. 2014;39(2):168-74.","Mizia-Stec K, Elzbieciak M, Wybraniec MT, Rozewicz M, Bodys A, Braksator W, et al. Chemotherapy and echocardiographic indices in patients with non-Hodgkin lymphoma: the ONCO-ECHO study. Med Oncol. 2017;35(1):14.","Dempke WCM, Zielinski R, Winkler C, Silberman S, Reuther S, Priebe W. Anthracycline-induced cardiotoxicity - are we about to clear this hurdle? Eur J Cancer. 2023 May;185:94\u2013104."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39008"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"566"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39008"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-22T17:30:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-22T17:31:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"566"}},"co